  "prompt": "How many First Ladies have refused to live in the White House?",
  "response": "As of my last update, there have been a few instances of First Ladies who chose not to live in the White House for various reasons:\n\n1. **Lady Bird Johnson** - While she lived in the White House, she often returned to Texas, and her preference was to spend time there.\n  \n2. **Pat Nixon** - She lived in the White House but expressed a desire to have a more private family life that didn't revolve solely around the presidency.\n\n3. **Nancy Reagan** - She lived in the White House but had her own circumstances that influenced her residence.\n\nHowever, relatively few First Ladies have outright refused to live in the White House altogether. The most notable case was **Emily Donelson**, who was a niece and hostess for her uncle, President James K. Polk, and she did not reside in the White House.\n\nOverall, it's uncommon for First Ladies to refuse to live in the White House, and instances are typically tied to personal circumstances or preferences. If you are looking for specific details or up-to-date information, it might be good to check the latest sources.",
